      </table>
      </div>
      <p><strong>Affiliate commission structure (per independent analysis, not confirmed on official sales pages):</strong> One independent reviewer documents a 20% level-one commission ($9.40 per active subscriber per month) and 5% at level two. This is an externally reported figure, not vendor-published data, and should be treated accordingly.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="design">
      <h2>Platform &amp; Build Quality</h2>
      <p>Megalink Traffic Rotator is a service subscription, not a software product. There is no dashboard to install, no application to download, and no interface to configure beyond the initial account-level setup inside OLSP. This is fundamentally different from standalone rotator tools like ClickMagick or Linkly, which give users a full control panel for managing destinations, weights, and tracking.</p>

      <h3>Service Infrastructure</h3>
      <p>The traffic originates from OLSP's existing solo ad operation. According to the official sales page, OLSP "sets aside a limited stream of traffic just for the Traffic Rotator program" from a broader daily visitor volume it describes as running to "tens of thousands" per day. Members' links are placed into this reserved stream; OLSP handles the routing entirely. We could not independently verify the size, composition, or quality of OLSP's traffic pool from publicly available information.</p>

      <h3>Trust Signals</h3>
      <p>The product is operated by Wayne Crowe Limited, a UK-registered entity identified in OLSP's official footer. Wayne Crowe has been publicly associated with online marketing and solo ads for approximately 15 years. The OLSP ecosystem has been running since around 2020 and has a documented public presence — products pages, community groups, and press materials — which establishes a baseline of operational continuity. That said, none of these signals constitute an independent audit of the service's traffic quality or results.</p>

      <h3>Long-Term Considerations</h3>
      <p>Because the service is entirely OLSP-operated with no external contract, any change to OLSP's pricing, traffic volume, or business model directly affects what subscribers receive. A subscriber's results are structurally dependent on OLSP maintaining its solo ad operation and rotator program at the described level — a concentration risk that standalone tracking tools (where the user controls the traffic source) do not carry.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="performance">
      <h2>Performance Analysis</h2>

      <h3>4.1 Core Functionality: How Traffic Reaches the Funnel</h3>
      <p>The mechanics can be described in four steps: OLSP reserves a pool of visitors from its solo ad operation specifically for rotator subscribers; each subscriber's Magick or Mega Link is placed into the rotation; OLSP routes a monthly share of those visitors to each link in turn; and those visitors enter the OLSP funnel, which handles list-building, upsell sequencing, and commission tracking on the subscriber's behalf.</p>

