      <h3>Setup Process</h3>
      <p>A community-produced guide inside the OLSP Facebook group describes the setup process as: activate your Magick Link ($7 entry product), configure a squeeze page using TD Pages or a compatible landing page builder, add that squeeze page link inside your OLSP account settings, then purchase the Traffic Rotator subscription. Once the subscription is active, OLSP adds the link to the rotation. The vendor describes no further technical action required from the subscriber.</p>
      <h3>Daily Usage</h3>
      <p>Once active, the service requires no ongoing management from the subscriber. OLSP handles traffic routing; the subscriber's role is to monitor funnel performance — opt-in rates, email open rates, and conversion rates through the Magick Link — and adjust their downstream sequences accordingly. The community guide cited above recommends tracking these metrics to determine whether the traffic is converting and whether the subscription is delivering value relative to cost.</p>
      <h3>Learning Curve</h3>
      <p>For a subscriber who already has a working OLSP funnel, adding the Traffic Rotator is described as straightforward. The complexity lies not in the service itself but in interpreting the results: understanding whether lower-than-expected conversions reflect traffic quality issues, funnel issues, or offer positioning requires marketing judgment that the service does not provide. First-time OLSP users should build that baseline understanding before adding a paid traffic subscription.</p>
      <h3>Transparency and Control</h3>
      <p>Compared to self-managed traffic tools, subscribers have limited visibility into how the rotator operates — there is no public documentation of the distribution algorithm, the traffic source composition, or per-subscriber allocation methodology. Independent tools like ClickMagick provide a full tracking dashboard; Megalink Traffic Rotator does not offer an equivalent level of subscriber-facing transparency.</p>
