    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What does "100% guaranteed commissions" actually mean?</summary>
        <p>Based on the sales page copy, this phrase appears to mean that OLSP pays a commission on every visitor routed through the subscriber's Magick Link — not that the subscriber is guaranteed a specific income level or a profitable return on the $47/month cost. No commission rate, earnings disclosure, or typical-results data accompanies the claim on the official sales page. We could not independently verify any income guarantee, and the phrase should be read as marketing language rather than a contractual promise.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I use Megalink Traffic Rotator to send traffic to non-OLSP destinations?</summary>
        <p>No. The official sales page explicitly states that the rotator is available only to Magick Link owners and routes traffic to Magick or Mega Link destinations within the OLSP ecosystem. It is not a general-purpose traffic service for external websites, standalone landing pages, or offers outside the OLSP funnel infrastructure.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does this compare to buying solo ads independently?</summary>
        <p>Independent solo ads give you control over vendor selection, traffic volume, and destination URL, and you can use a third-party tracker like ClickMagick to audit results. Megalink Traffic Rotator is simpler to set up and requires no vendor research, but in exchange you receive no visibility into traffic source composition or per-click data. Independent solo ads are more transparent; Megalink Traffic Rotator is more hands-off. Independent analysts generally recommend solo ads or other verifiable traffic sources while building a funnel, and the Traffic Rotator as an add-on once the funnel is proven.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is this worth buying as a beginner to OLSP?</summary>
        <p>Multiple independent reviewers say no — and the reasoning is consistent. A beginner who has not yet validated their funnel will not be able to distinguish poor traffic quality from poor funnel performance. Paying $47/month before that diagnostic baseline exists adds cost without clarifying the problem. Independent analysis recommends waiting until OLSP commissions reach at least a few hundred dollars per month before adding a paid traffic subscription, at which point the rotator's split-testing utility becomes meaningful.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

